<DOC><DOCNO> AP900227-0141 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-90 1929EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Airport     02-27 0209</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Japan-Airport,0214</SECOND><HEAD>Airport Foes Suspected as Construction Executive's Home Burns</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Fire destroyed the home of a construction companypresident early Tuesday, and police said they believed radicalsopposing expansion of Tokyo's international airport may have setthe blaze.   Investigators found two timer devices, plastic vessels andelectric wires in the wreckage of the two-story wooden housebelonging to Teruzo Yoshino, president of Shimizu Corp., a leadingconstruction firm. Yoshino and his wife were at home when the firestarted at 3:20 a.m. but fled to safety, said a police officialspeaking on condition of anonymity.   Shimizu Corp. is building a new airport terminal jointly withother Japanese firms in a project to expand the airport, whichopened in 1978 at Narita, 40 miles northeast of Tokyo.   The government plans to build the terminal and two additionalrunways by the end of March 1991 at an estimated cost of $4 billionto cope with existing overcrowding and demands for even moreflights from the airport.   But eight farmers still live on the planned expansion site andrefuse to leave.   Farmers and their supporters, including radicals seizing on theissue for their anti-government activities, have been resisting thegovernment's plans to expropriate farmland to expand the airport.</TEXT></DOC>